The Ukraine on the Way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," said Rudyard Kipling once.
The Ukraine is indeed located in the East, but in the East of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the main goal for many of us.
The path to it, however, was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go this way.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union I was quite successful.
There is no doubt for me that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties of Ukraine in finding accession to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural cultivation areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machine parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture according to the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We have messed up the reform all by ourselves.
Because often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy - in a weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the Parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is somewhat akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has gained momentum, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
You can see that on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to find safety from thoughtless drivers).
In Kiev there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German and French, they can handle computers and surf the net in internet cafes.
But these are just the sentimental digressions of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The sober look of the professional politician, which I am, sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, there has been a development from total rejection of reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms driven by corrupt motives to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very vividly.
Initially, the reform of the state provoked a hostile attitude both among bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "Formula F" reform: the state must shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would already run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better by simply wielding the red pen led us to the second stage in our reform process.
Slowly, the state was reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
The work of the government ministries was stabilized thereby.
At the beginning, the authority delegated to these new areas was somewhat too broad to shape their work more effectively.
Now they more or less function normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes annoy themselves with these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (albeit reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians accept them as well.
Only radicals and populists - of which there are still far too many among us - can afford to take an indifferent attitude toward a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a by-product of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial person cannot under any circumstances admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
In the measure that we shed our provincial impulse to have to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians have had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even more ill, but the recent elections, which have deprived the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the edge of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalized people.
As the great and at that time already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all nature's achievements, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous journey to Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
